Halve, peel, and thinly slice half the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Slice the @celery{1%stalk} as thin as possible. Halve the @fennel{1%bunch}(halved lengthwise, core removed) and remove the core. Then, thinly slice widthwise. Finely chop the @mint{1%sprig}(finely chopped) and @parsley{1%bunch}(finely chopped).

Working over a #bowl{}, zest the @orange{1}(zested) and peel it by running your knife between the white pith and the flesh with a small #paring knife{}. Then, cut the orange into segments by holding the orange in one hand and with the other, cut along both sides of the membranes to release the segments. Squeeze the remaining orange to collect any extra juice for the dressing. Tear the segments into bite sized pieces.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #pot{} over medium heat. Add half the sliced onion to the pot. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes}, until soft.

Meanwhile, toss remaining sliced onion in a bowl with the @white wine vinegar{2%tbsp}; set aside.

When the onion is soft, add the @pearled couscous{3/4%cup} to the pot and toss until toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add the @veggie stock concentrate{1} and @water{2%cups} to the pot, bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer until couscous is al dente, ~{8-10%minutes}. Drain any excess liquid.

Meanwhile, in a bowl, combine couscous, orange zest, orange juice, orange segments, fennel, celery, mint, parsley and as much pickled red onion as you like. Toss and season with salt and pepper.

Drizzle with @olive oil{1%tbsp} and a sprinkle of @feta cheese{1/4%cup} and @pepitas{1%oz}.

> Fennel and orange is a classic flavor combo. Pearled couscous is the perfect base for refreshing herbs, salty feta, and crunchy pepitas.